hook.real_world_problem:
Flipkart has 10 app instances each with Caffeine L1 cache (0.01ms reads). When Seller A updates product P001's price from ₹999 to ₹799:

```
Instance 1: processes update → refreshes its L1 cache → ₹799 ✓
Instance 2: L1 cache: ₹999 ← STALE! (TTL: 29 minutes remaining)
Instance 3: L1 cache: ₹999 ← STALE!
...
Instance 10: L1 cache: ₹999 ← STALE!

For the next 29 minutes:
  ~10% of requests → Instance 1 → ₹799 (correct)
  ~90% of requests → Instances 2-10 → ₹999 (wrong price!)
  Some users see old price, some see new price
  Customer complains: 'I see ₹999 but my friend sees ₹799 for the same product'
```

**Redis Pub/Sub broadcasts the invalidation instantly to ALL instances:**
```java
// When price updates on Instance 1:
@CacheEvict(value="products", key="#productId")
public Product updatePrice(String productId, double newPrice) {
    Product updated = productRepo.update(productId, newPrice);
    // Broadcast to all other instances:
    redisTemplate.convertAndSend(
        "cache.invalidate.products",  // channel
        productId                      // message
    );
    return updated;
}

// ALL 10 instances are subscribed to this channel:
@Bean
public MessageListenerAdapter listener(CacheInvalidationHandler handler) {
    return new MessageListenerAdapter(handler, "handleInvalidation");
}
// When message arrives: evict from L1 cache
// Result: all 10 instances serve ₹799 within milliseconds
```

concept_explanation.pubsub_basics:
**Redis Pub/Sub — how it works:**

```
Publisher (Instance 1):
  PUBLISH cache.invalidate.products 'P001'
  → Redis delivers to all current subscribers

Subscribers (ALL 10 instances):
  SUBSCRIBE cache.invalidate.products
  → Receive message 'P001'
  → Evict P001 from their L1 cache
  → Next request for P001: L1 miss → Redis L2 → serves fresh data

Key properties:
  Fire-and-forget: publisher doesn't know how many subscribers received it
  At-most-once: if subscriber is offline when message is published, it misses it
  Fan-out: one PUBLISH delivers to ALL subscribers simultaneously
  Fast: sub-millisecond delivery within same Redis server
```

**Spring Data Redis Pub/Sub configuration:**
```java
@Configuration
public class RedisPubSubConfig {

    // 1. Message handler:
    @Bean
    public CacheInvalidationHandler cacheInvalidationHandler(
            CacheManager cacheManager) {
        return new CacheInvalidationHandler(cacheManager);
    }

    // 2. Adapter: bridges Redis message to Java method call:
    @Bean
    public MessageListenerAdapter messageListenerAdapter(
            CacheInvalidationHandler handler) {
        return new MessageListenerAdapter(handler, "onMessage");
        // 'onMessage' = method name on CacheInvalidationHandler
    }

    // 3. Container: manages subscriptions and thread pool:
    @Bean
    public RedisMessageListenerContainer container(
            RedisConnectionFactory factory,
            MessageListenerAdapter adapter) {
        RedisMessageListenerContainer container =
            new RedisMessageListenerContainer();
        container.setConnectionFactory(factory);
        container.addMessageListener(
            adapter,
            new PatternTopic("cache.invalidate.*")  // subscribe to all 'cache.invalidate.*' channels
        );
        return container;
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.publish_and_subscribe:
**Publishing and handling invalidation events:**

```java
// PUBLISHER — runs when cache should be invalidated:
@Service
public class ProductService {
    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    private final ProductRepository repo;
    private final CacheManager cacheManager;

    @Transactional
    public Product updateProduct(Product product) {
        Product saved = repo.save(product);

        // Evict OUR local L1 cache:
        Cache l1 = cacheManager.getCache("products");
        if (l1 != null) l1.evict(product.getId());

        // Broadcast to ALL other instances via Pub/Sub:
        redis.convertAndSend(
            "cache.invalidate.products",  // channel name
            product.getId()               // message = product ID
        );

        return saved;
    }
}

// SUBSCRIBER — runs on EVERY instance when message arrives:
@Component
public class CacheInvalidationHandler {
    private final CacheManager cacheManager;

    CacheInvalidationHandler(CacheManager cm) { cacheManager = cm; }

    // This method is called by MessageListenerAdapter on every message:
    public void onMessage(String message) {
        // message = productId from publisher
        System.out.println("[PubSub] Invalidating product: " + message);

        Cache products = cacheManager.getCache("products");
        if (products != null) {
            products.evict(message);  // evict this product from L1
        }
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.channel_patterns:
**Channel naming and topic patterns:**

```java
// Specific channel:
new ChannelTopic("cache.invalidate.products")  // only products channel

// Pattern (wildcard subscription):
new PatternTopic("cache.invalidate.*")  // ALL cache.invalidate.* channels
// Matches:
//   cache.invalidate.products
//   cache.invalidate.categories
//   cache.invalidate.prices

// Multi-channel handler:
@Component
public class MultiCacheInvalidationHandler implements MessageListener {
    private final CacheManager cacheManager;

    @Override
    public void onMessage(Message message, byte[] pattern) {
        String channel = new String(message.getChannel());
        String body    = new String(message.getBody());

        // Extract cache name from channel:
        // 'cache.invalidate.products' → cache name = 'products'
        if (channel.contains(".")) {
            String cacheName = channel.substring(channel.lastIndexOf('.') + 1);
            Cache cache = cacheManager.getCache(cacheName);
            if (cache != null) {
                if ("*".equals(body)) {
                    cache.clear();         // broadcast 'clear all'
                } else {
                    cache.evict(body);     // evict specific key
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.testing_pubsub:
**Testing Pub/Sub with CountDownLatch:**

```java
@SpringBootTest
class CachePubSubTest {
    @Autowired RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    @Autowired CacheManager cacheManager;

    @Test
    void publishInvalidation_evictsFromAllSubscribers() throws Exception {
        // Arrange — put something in cache:
        Cache cache = cacheManager.getCache("products");
        cache.put("P001", "Wireless Mouse ₹799");
        assertNotNull(cache.get("P001"));  // in cache

        // CountDownLatch: wait for async subscriber to process message
        CountDownLatch latch = new CountDownLatch(1);

        // Override handler for this test to count down:
        // (In practice: spy or use the actual handler)

        // Act — publish invalidation:
        redis.convertAndSend("cache.invalidate.products", "P001");

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for subscriber to process:
        boolean received = latch.await(2, TimeUnit.SECONDS);

        // Assert — small sleep for async processing:
        Thread.sleep(100);
        assertNull(cache.get("P001"), "P001 should be evicted from cache");
    }
}
```

